# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: truffle-suite
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] An **application binary interface** (**ABI**) is an interface exposed by software that is defined for in-process machine code access.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Often, the exposing software is a library, and the consumer is a program.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] An ABI is at a relatively low level of abstraction.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Interface compatibility depends on the target hardware and the software build toolchain.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] In contrast, an application programming interface (API) defines access in source code, which is a relatively high-level, hardware-independent, and human-readable format.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] An API defines an interface at the source code level, before compilation, whereas an ABI defines an interface to compiled code.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] API compatibility is generally the concern for system design and of the toolchain.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] However, a programmer may have to deal with an ABI directly when writing a program in multiple languages or when using multiple compilers for the same language.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] A complete ABI enables a program that supports an ABI to run without modification on multiple operating systems that provide the ABI.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] The target system must provide any required libraries (that implement the ABI), and there may be other prerequisites.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] ABIs include the Intel Binary Compatibility Standard (iBCS) and the System V Release 4 ABIs for various instruction sets.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] An **embedded ABI** (**EABI**), used on an embedded operating system, specifies aspects such as file formats, data types, register usage, stack frame organization, and function parameter passing of an embedded software program.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Each compiler and assembler that supports an EABI creates object code that is compatible with code generated by other such compilers and assemblers.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] This allows developers to link libraries generated by one compiler with object code generated by another.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Typically, an EABI is optimized for performance for the limited resources of the target embedded system.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Therefore, an EABI may omit abstractions between kernel and user space typically found in desktop operating systems.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] The choice of EABI can affect performance.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Widely used EABIs include the PowerPC, Arm, and MIPS EABIs.
[src:truffle-suite/application-binary-interface] Specific software implementations like the C library may impose additional limitations to form more concrete ABIs; one example is the GNU OABI and EABI for ARM, both of which are subsets of the ARM EABI.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:truffle-suite/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:truffle-suite/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:truffle-suite/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity was proposed in August 2014 by Gavin Wood The language was later developed by the Ethereum project's Solidity team, led by Christian Reitwiessner.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity is the primary language used to develop smart contracts for Ethereum and other private blockchains, such as the enterprise-oriented Hyperledger Fabric blockchain.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] SWIFT deployed a proof of concept using Solidity running on Hyperledger Fabric.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity is a statically typed programming language designed for developing smart contracts that run on the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) or compatible virtual machines.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity uses ECMAScript-like syntax which makes it familiar for web developers; however unlike ECMAScript it has static typing and variadic return types.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity is different from other EVM-targeting languages such as Serpent and Mutan in some important ways.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] It supports complex member variables for smart contracts, including arbitrarily hierarchical mappings and structs.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity smart contract support inheritance, including multiple inheritance with C3 linearization.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity introduces an application binary interface (ABI) that facilitates multiple type-safe functions within one smart contract (this was also later supported by Serpent).
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] The Solidity proposal also includes "Natural Language Specification", a documentation system for specifying user-centric descriptions of the ramifications of method-calls.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Many security properties of smart contracts are inherently difficult to reason about directly, and the Turing-completeness of Solidity means that verification of arbitrary properties cannot be decidably automated.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Current automated solutions for smart contract security analysis can miss critical violations, produce false positives, and fail to achieve sufficient code coverage on realistic contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] Solidity has been blamed for the error-prone implementation of Ethereum smart contracts due to its counterintuitive nature, its lack of constructs to deal with blockchain domain-specific aspects, and its lack of centralized documentation of known vulnerabilities.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] In 2016, a Cornell University researcher stated that Solidity was partly to blame for The DAO hack that occurred that year.
[src:truffle-suite/solidity] The developers community often cites Solidity requiring much of third party interfaces and APIs, and its inability to create critical information intensive smart contracts.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Academic surveys describe Web3 as combining smart contract platforms, peer-to-peer networks, and cryptographic mechanisms, while noting trade-offs involving scalability, interoperability, and governance.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Critics have expressed concerns over the centralization of wealth to a small group of investors and individuals, or a loss of privacy due to more expansive data collection.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Billionaires like Elon Musk and Jack Dorsey have argued that web3 only serves as a buzzword or marketing term.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web 1.0 and Web 2.0 refer to eras in the history of the World Wide Web as it evolved through various technologies and formats.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web 1.0 refers roughly to the period from 1991 to 2004, where most sites consisted of static pages, and the vast majority of users were consumers, not producers of content.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web 2.0 is based around the idea of "the web as platform" and centers on user-created content uploaded to forums, social media and networking services, blogs, and wikis, among other services.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web 2.0 is generally considered to have begun around 2004 and continues to the current day.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web3 is distinct from Tim Berners-Lee's 1999 concept of a Semantic Web, which was also sometimes referred to as Web 3.0.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] While the Semantic Web envisioned a web of linked data, web3 in the blockchain context refers to a decentralized internet built upon distributed ledger technologies.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Ethereum co-founder Gavin Wood first popularized the use of the term Web 3.0 in a blockchain context in 2014.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Wood used the term to refer to a "decentralized online ecosystem based on blockchain." "Web3" and "Web 3.0" have been used interchangeably by later writers, leading to confusion between the two concepts.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] In popular and industry usage, "Web 3.0" is sometimes used interchangeably with "web3" to refer to blockchain-based proposals rather than the Semantic Web.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] The definition of the term has been described by *Bloomberg* journalist Olga Kharif as "hazy", but it revolves around the idea of decentralization and often incorporate blockchain technologies, such as various cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Kharif has described web3 as an idea that "would build financial assets, in the form of tokens, into the inner workings of almost anything you do online".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web3 has been proposed as a possible response to the over-centralization of the web in a few Big Tech companies.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web3 could potentially improve data security, scalability, and privacy.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] According Kharif in December 2021, skeptics say the idea "is a long way from proving its use beyond niche applications, many of them tools aimed at crypto traders".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] DuPont et al (2024) describe web3 as an umbrella term for NFTs, cryptocurrency, and blockchain which appeals to users who are "not necessarily plugged into the cypher-punk or crypto-anarchist ideals of Bitcoin".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Rohn (2025) describes the term as synonymous with "blockchain economy".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] In 2019, *The Conversation* quoted legal scholars discussing concerns over the difficulty of regulating a decentralized web, which they reported might make it more difficult to prevent cybercrime, online harassment, hate speech, and the dissemination of child sexual abuse material.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] The concept of Web3 has also been described as a part of a cryptocurrency bubble, and as an extension of harmful and short-lived blockchain-based trends such as NFTs.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] The use of cryptocurrencies, NFTs, and blockchains in general also introduce potential harmful environmental effects.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Others have expressed beliefs that web3 and the associated technologies are a pyramid scheme.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Web3 proposals often include decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs) and decentralized finance (DeFi).
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Marlinspike also remarked that the new web resembles the old web.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] In 2021, interest in the web3 concept began to increase.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Particular interest spiked toward the end of 2021, largely due to interest from cryptocurrency enthusiasts and investments from high-profile technologists and companies.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Executives from venture capital firm Andreessen Horowitz traveled to Washington, DC, in October 2021 to lobby for the idea as a potential solution to questions about regulation of the web, with which policymakers have been grappling.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] *The New York Times* and *Fortune* reported in December 2021 that $27 billion had been invested in blockchain projects due to interest in the Web3 concept.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] In late 2021, Reddit, Discord, and other Web 2.0 companies experimented with incorporating web3 technologies into their platforms.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] On November 8, 2021, Discord CEO Jason Citron tweeted a screenshot suggesting the platform might be integrating cryptocurrency wallets into their platform.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Two days later, and after heavy user backlash, Discord announced they had no plans to integrate such technologies and that it was an internal-only concept that had been developed in a company-wide hackathon.
[src:truffle-suite/web3] It's what parents tell their kids about at night if they want them to grow up to become economists".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] That same month, Jack Dorsey, co-founder and former CEO of Twitter, dismissed web3 as a "venture capitalists' plaything".
[src:truffle-suite/web3] Dorsey opined that web3 will not democratize the internet, but it will shift power from players like Facebook to venture capital funds like Andreessen Horowitz.
